We could do that in C++, but I have two concerns. 1) It adds some complication and also runtime cost (spawning an external subprocess). 2) It sets an environment variable from a library.

Another thing we can do is simply document how to set the CLASSPATH from a command line, which is actually simple. For example on a Unix shell:
{code}
export CLASSPATH=$($HADOOP_HOME/bin/hadoop classpath --glob)
{code}

On a Windows shell this might be (untested):
{code}
%HADOOP_HOME%/bin/hadoop classpath --glob > %CLASSPATH%
{code}
